{{Infobox person |image = Debbie Lee Carrington 2010.jpg | imagesize = 220px | caption = Carrington in 2010 | birth_date = {{Birth date |1959|12|14}} | birth_name = Deborah Lee Carrington | birth_place = [[San Jose, California]], [[United States|U.S.]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2018|3|23|1959|12|14}} | death_place = [[Pleasanton, California]], U.S. | years_active = 1981–2018 | occupation = Actress, stuntwoman }} '''Deborah "Debbie" Lee Carrington''' (December 14, 1959{{spnd}} March 23, 2018)<ref>[https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3490217/actress-stuntwoman-debbie-lee-carrington-passed-away/ Actress and Stuntwoman Debbie Lee Carrington Has Passed Away] ''Bloody Disgusting'', March 24, 2018</ref><ref name="Variety">[https://variety.com/2018/biz/obituaries-people-news/deborah-carrington-dead-dies-total-recall-1202739869/ Deborah JCarrington, Stuntwoman and ‘Total Recall’ Actress, Dies at 58] Kirsten Chuba, variety.com, March 29, 2018. Retrieved June 29, 2019</ref> was an American actress and [[stuntwoman]]. Her best known movie roles include playing a Martian rebel in ''[[Total Recall (1990 film)|Total Recall]]'', an [[Ewok]] in ''[[Return of the Jedi]]'' (and in subsequent TV movies) and an elf in ''[[The Polar Express (film)|The Polar Express]]''.<ref name="NYTimes">NY Times Obituary, March 29, 2018 https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/29/obituaries/deborah-carrington-58-dies-actress-and-stuntwoman.html</ref>
She was born in [[San Jose, California]]; her father was an insurance manager and her mother was a schoolteacher.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/24/Debbie-Lee-Carrington.html Debbie Lee Carrington Biography]</ref> While attending the University of California-Davis, she replied to an ad for extras in a newsletter published by Little People of America for ''[[Under the Rainbow]]'', a film about the [[Munchkin]]s from ''The Wizard of Oz''. Having landed a role in the film, she took a break from her studies, but later returned and gained a degree in early childhood development.<ref>Obituary, The Independent https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/debbie-lee-carrington-dies-actress-total-recall-star-wars-age-58-a8281746.html</ref>
==Early life and career== She appeared in many other films and TV shows, including ''[[In Living Color]]'', ''[[The Drew Carey Show]]'', ''[[Howard the Duck (film)|Howard the Duck]]'', ''[[Tracey Takes On...]]'', ''[[Men in Black (1997 film)|Men in Black]]'', ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[Baywatch]]'', ''[[Married... with Children]]'', ''[[Boston Legal]]'', ''[[The Garbage Pail Kids Movie]]'', ''[[Dexter (TV series)|Dexter]]'', and ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]''. In 2008, she filmed scenes for the action thriller ''[[Bitch Slap]]''.<ref name="LAT">{{cite news|url=http://www.bitchslapmovie.com/press/LATimes01.jpg|title=David Strick's Hollywood Backlot|date=2008-06-12|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Company|accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref> She also performed as a stunt double – often for child actors and dolls that had come to life – in films like [[Titanic (1997 film)]] and the ''Child's Play'' slasher film series.<ref>NY Times Obituary, March 29, 2018 https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/29/obituaries/deborah-carrington-58-dies-actress-and-stuntwoman.html </ref>
Carrington was born with [[dwarfism]] and said she had experienced prejudicial attitudes as a dwarf in Hollywood. She supported other dwarf actors, insisting that they received credit for their work, since many costume-specific parts often went uncredited.
By the 1990s, Carrington began to push back against being typecast in costume-only roles. On television, she played character roles like Tiny Avenger on ''[[In Living Color]]'', Tammy in ''[[Seinfeld]]'', and Doreen in ''[[The Drew Carey Show]]''.<ref>NY Times Obituary, March 29, 2018 https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/29/obituaries/deborah-carrington-58-dies-actress-and-stuntwoman.html</ref> ==Death== Carrington died on March 23, 2018, at age 58 on her parents' ranch in [[Pleasanton, California]] following a period of health complications.<ref name="Variety" /><ref name="NYTimes" />
